Looking at the Hexi library's buffer adaptor interface, I can see that it provides methods for advancing the read position. Here's the complete implementation:

```cpp
#include <hexi/pmc/buffer_adaptor.h>
#include <vector>
#include <cstdint>

void skip_bytes_in_buffer(hexi::pmc::buffer_adaptor<std::vector<std::byte>>& buffer, std::size_t bytes) {
    buffer.advance_read(bytes);
}

struct MessageHeader {
    uint16_t message_type;
    uint32_t body_length;
};

MessageHeader read_header_and_skip_body(hexi::pmc::buffer_adaptor<std::vector<std::byte>>& buffer) {
    MessageHeader header;

    // Read the message_type (2 bytes)
    buffer.read(reinterpret_cast<std::byte*>(&header.message_type), sizeof(header.message_type));

    // Read the body_length (4 bytes)  
    buffer.read(reinterpret_cast<std::byte*>(&header.body_length), sizeof(header.body_length));

    // Skip the body based on the length field
    skip_bytes_in_buffer(buffer, header.body_length);

    return header;
}
```

The implementation uses:
- `advance_read()` to skip bytes in the buffer without reading them
- `read()` method to read the header fields from the buffer
- Proper casting using `reinterpret_cast` to read into the struct fields
- The `skip_bytes_in_buffer` function to skip the body data after reading the header

This follows the Hexi library's buffer adaptor interface pattern shown in the code fragments, where the adaptor manages read/write positions and provides methods for advancing through the buffer.

