Based on the code fragments and the Hexi library documentation, here's the implementation of the requested functions:

```cpp
#include <hexi/pmc/buffer_adaptor.h>
#include <hexi/shared.h>
#include <vector>
#include <cstdint>

bool check_can_write_seek(hexi::pmc::buffer_adaptor<std::vector<std::byte>>& buffer) {
    return buffer.can_write_seek();
}

void seek_write_position(hexi::pmc::buffer_adaptor<std::vector<std::byte>>& buffer, hexi::buffer_seek direction, std::size_t offset) {
    buffer.write_seek(direction, offset);
}

void update_header_at_position(hexi::pmc::buffer_adaptor<std::vector<std::byte>>& buffer, uint32_t header_value) {
    // Save current write position
    buffer.write_seek(hexi::buffer_seek::current, 0);

    // Write header placeholder (zeros) at the beginning
    buffer.write_seek(hexi::buffer_seek::begin, 0);
    uint32_t placeholder = 0;
    buffer.write(&placeholder, sizeof(placeholder));

    // Write the body content (example: some data after the header)
    // This would typically be the actual payload data
    std::vector<std::byte> body_data = {std::byte{0x01}, std::byte{0x02}, std::byte{0x03}, std::byte{0x04}};
    buffer.write(body_data.data(), body_data.size());

    // Seek back to beginning to update the header with the actual value
    buffer.write_seek(hexi::buffer_seek::begin, 0);
    buffer.write(&header_value, sizeof(header_value));

    // Seek back to the end to continue writing (optional)
    buffer.write_seek(hexi::buffer_seek::end, 0);
}
```

**Explanation:**

1. **`check_can_write_seek`**: Simply calls the `can_write_seek()` method from the `buffer_write` base class to check if the buffer supports write seeking.

2. **`seek_write_position`**: Uses the `write_seek()` method with the provided direction (`buffer_seek::begin`, `buffer_seek::current`, or `buffer_seek::end`) and offset to move the write position.

3. **`update_header_at_position`**: Implements the pattern of:
   - Saving the current position (though in this case we just note it)
   - Writing a header placeholder at the beginning
   - Writing the body content
   - Seeking back to update the header with the actual value
   - Optionally seeking to the end to continue writing

The `buffer_seek` enum (from the code fragments) likely has values like:
- `buffer_seek::begin` - seek from the beginning of the buffer
- `buffer_seek::current` - seek from the current position  
- `buffer_seek::end` - seek from the end of the buffer

This implementation follows the typical pattern for writing data structures where you need to write a header first but don't know the final header value until after writing the body content.

